CatDescriptText: Mr. Lee Jackson, porter, East Liberty and Mr. D.J. O'Connor, foreman, North Side, were part of the Pittsburghers Speak Up column published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, December 16, 1961, pg. 7 with question: "Do you think the so-called 'store-front' churches, and those who are known generally as 'self-styled preachers,' are an asset or a liability to the community." Mr. Lee Jackson's answer reads: "No comment.  I don't get mixed up in church affairs."  Mr. D.J. O'Connor's answer reads: "I think they are assets.  Anybody and anything which has helped people to some religion and to come into the church and has helped them in anyway, is an asset."
TitMainTitle: Two frames: Portrait of Lee Jackson wearing cap with shield insignia and zippered jacket, posed in front of ribbed metal wall; Portrait of D.J. O'Connor wearing light colored fedora and eyeglasses, standing on sidewalk, Downtown
